\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3.1.14â€“3.1.16
\end_layout

\end_inset

For each of the following matrices,
 find vectors that span the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Give as few vectors as possible.
 You do not need to explain why this is the smallest possible number of vectors.
 
\shape italic
Hint:
 Drawing a figure might be helpful.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3\\
1 & 2 & 3\\
1 & 2 & 3
\end{bmatrix},\quad B=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1 & 1 & 1\\
1 & 2 & 3 & 4
\end{bmatrix},\quad C=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
1 & 2\\
1 & 3\\
1 & 4
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

,
 all three vectors are in the straight line 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=z$
\end_inset

,
 so any linear combination of these vectors is in this line,
 which is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1,1)$
\end_inset

,
 so this is my answer for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

,
 the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2)$
\end_inset

 are already enough to cover the whole plane because the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1,1)x+(1,2)y=(a,b)
\]

\end_inset

has a solution no matter the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 (namely,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2a-b$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=b-a$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore,
 the image of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the entire plane,
 and an example of a spanning set is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(1,0),(0,1)\}$
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(1,1),(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

,
 the two vectors are not aligned,
 so they form a plane.
 So we won't be able to reduce the number of vectors,
 and so my answer to this one is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(1,1,1,1),(1,2,3,4)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
3.3.4
\end_layout

\end_inset

Consider the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 4\\
2 & 8
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
Find all of the following:
 A basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\im A$
\end_inset

,
 the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\im A$
\end_inset

,
 a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker A$
\end_inset

,
 and the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker A$
\end_inset

.
 Write out the equality that the rank-nullity theorem gives you in this case (for example:
 
\begin_inset Formula $1+2=3$
\end_inset

,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $2+0=2$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 we row-reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
\begin{array}{c}
\\R_{2}-2R_{1}
\end{array} & \begin{bmatrix}1 & 4\\
2 & 8
\end{bmatrix}\\
\text{In row-reduced form. Pivot highlighted.} & \begin{bmatrix}\text{\fbox{1}} & 4\\
0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

To get a basis for the image,
 we take the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the pivots.
 So,
 a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $\im A$
\end_inset

 is:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(1,2)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Also,
 the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\im A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For the kernel:
 The dimension of the kernel is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

,
 because this is the number of non-pivot columns.
 By the procedure given in class,
 a basis for the kernel could be:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(-4,1)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
The equality given by the rank-nullity theorem is:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rk A+\nullity A=\width A$
\end_inset

,
 which in this case is 
\begin_inset Formula $1+1=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
